<article>
    <h1>Quibi mulls over sale as it strug&#xAD;gles to at&#xAD;tract sub&#xAD;scribers</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200926/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-09-26"><time>2020-09-26</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE TRENDING</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>UNITED STATES • Quibi, the short-video up­start founded by Hol­ly­wood heavy­weight Jef­frey Katzen­berg, is work­ing with an ad­viser to con­sider its next steps af­ter fail­ing to meet sub­scriber tar­gets, The Wall Street Jour­nal re­ported.</p>
    <p>The op­tions in­clude a po­ten­tial sale, rais­ing more money or go­ing pub­lic through a merger with a spe­cial-pur­pose ac­qui­si­tion com­pany, the news­pa­per said, cit­ing uniden­ti­fied peo­ple fa­mil­iar with the sit­u­a­tion.</p>
    <p>The re­port is the lat­est sign that things are not go­ing ac­cord­ing to plan for the much-bal­ly­hooed video startup, which launched in April with the goal of en­ter­tain­ing peo­ple dur­ing com­mutes and other dull mo­ments – like a wait at the den­tist’s of­fice. With most peo­ple at home dur­ing the pan­demic, the app has strug­gled to at­tract sub­scribers and com­pete with a raft of other pop­u­lar stream­ing ser­vices.</p>
    <p>That is de­spite the star power of the videos on the plat­form, which feature some of Hol­ly­wood’s top ac­tors and co­me­di­ans.</p>
    <p>Quibi has raised US$1.8 bil­lion (S$2.5 bil­lion) from in­vestors, in­clud­ing many of the big­gest me­dia giants, and is run by Sil­i­con Val­ley vet­eran Meg Whit­man.</p>
    <p>Rep­re­sen­ta­tives for Quibi de­clined to com­ment on the “ru­mour and spec­u­la­tion” in the Jour­nal’s re­port.</p>
    <p>The app has also re­vamped some of its pro­gram­ming, fo­cus­ing on what has res­onated with sub­scribers, peo­ple fa­mil­iar with the mat­ter said in May.</p>
    <p>Its pro­grammes are sorted into three groups: movies told in chap­ters, episodic un­scripted pro­grammes and “daily es­sen­tials”. Daily es­sen­tials, brief news up­dates daily, have been less pop­u­lar, Mr Katzen­berg told The New York Times ear­lier this year.</p>
    <p>The ser­vice re­ceived two Cre­ative Arts Em­mys for a po­lice drama called #FreeRaysha­wn.</p>


